dataset.display: Age-Adjusted Rate Adults - 65 Yrs and Older
dataset.measure: Age-Adjusted Rate Adults - 65 Yrs and Older
dataset.how_calculated:
Number of NYC resident adults 65 years and older hospitalized for heart attack (acute myocardial infarction), summed within 5-year age groups, and divided by the population in each age group, using NYC DOHMH intercensal estimates; quotients are multiplied by the proportion of the 2000 US population in each age group. Age-adjusted rate is the sum of the weighted age-specific rates; expressed as cases per 10,000 residents. 

 

A hospitalization is included if it has an ICD-9 principal diagnosis code of 410 or an ICD-10 rincipal diagnosis code of I21 or I22 and excluded if the patient was transfered from one urgrent care facility within NYC to another.

show_disparities_node.disparitiesPagetext: When population health or the quality of living environments varies by population characteristics such as income or race, there is disparity. One way to visualize disparity is to chart indicators of health or environment across levels of neighborhood poverty. We categorized neighborhoods as high, medium or low poverty. Then we took the median of the neighborhood-specific values in each category. The median is the middle of the sorted group of values.

info.info_how_calculated: Neighborhoods are ranked according to the percent of people whose annual income falls below 100% of the federal poverty level. Rankings are then divided into 3 approximately equal groupings of low, medium and high poverty.
info.info_source: American Community Survey

link_data_node.linkDataPagetext: The "Link Data" function shows associations between environmental health data at the neighborhood level using <a href="http://a816-dohbesp.nyc.gov/IndicatorPublic/Glossary.aspx?#Scatterplot" target="_blank">scatterplots.</a> The points represent x and y values for each NYC neighborhood. The pairs of indicators available for scatterplots were chosen because previous research suggests that one may either directly or indirectly cause or contribute to the other. Because the data being charted are <a href="http://a816-dohbesp.nyc.gov/IndicatorPublic/Glossary.aspx?#Ecological_Study" target="_blank">ecological</a> and not individual level, and because many factors contribute to the health of a population or environment, the patterns seen in these charts do not necessarily represent the underlying causal relationship.
link_data_node.Measure: Age-Adjusted Rate Adults - 65 Yrs and Older

Number of NYC resident adults 35 to 64 years old hospitalized for heart attack (acute myocardial infarction), summed within 5-year age groups, and divided by the population in each age group, using NYC DOHMH intercensal estimates; quotients are multiplied by the proportion of the 2000 US population in each age group. Age-adjusted rate is the sum of the weighted age-specific rates; expressed as cases per 10,000 residents.

 

A hospitalization is included if it has an ICD-9 principal diagnosis code of 410 or an ICD-10 rincipal diagnosis code of I21 or I22 and excluded if the patient was transfered from one urgrent care facility within NYC to another.
info.info_source: New York State Statewide Planning and Research Cooperative System (SPARCS) Deidentified Hospital Discharge Data

info.info_how_calculated: Air samples collected at specific NYCCAS monitoring sites along with information about emissions sources were incorporated into a statistical model that predicted pollutant concentrations at all locations in NYC for the specified time period. The results were then assigned to the appropriate NYC neighborhood and averaged. Black carbon levels are estimated using a method that measures absorbance.
info.info_source: New York City Community Air Survey

info.info_name: Children under 6 years with elevated blood lead levels (BLL)
info.info_how_calculated: Number of children less than 6 years old tested in a given year with blood lead levels of 5 mcg/dL or greater, divided by the total number of children less than 6 years old who were tested for lead poisoning in a given year; expressed as cases per 1,000 tested. The numbers in this table include all children tested within a given calendar year, regardless of whether they were tested in previous years with the same or different blood lead levels. While children can receive more than one test during the calendar year, children are only counted once using the highest confirmed blood lead level during the calendar year. If the child does not have a confirmed test in a given year, the childs blood lead level is based on the highest capillary or unknown test type. This measure differs from the rate of children newly identified with blood lead levels at or above a certain level reported by the Health Department in other publications. Read more about different measures used by the Health Department for surveillance of childhood lead poisoning.
info.info_source: New York City Healthy Homes Program
